subsection.p:
Now,  if we wanted the magnitude and direction of the sum vector,  we  can just use the  (x,y)  to  (r, \theta) transformations, as we do for any vector.

	  \amp r_{\text{sum}} =  \sqrt{ x_{\text{sum}}^2 + y_{\text{sum}}^2 }
	  \amp \tan \theta_{\text{sum}} =  \dfrac{ y_{\text{sum}} }{ x_{\text{sum}} } 

Once we get the angle, we deduce the direction from the angle value based on the quadrant the vector is pointed, and then we state the direction as clockwise or counterclockwise angles from Cartesian axes.

solution.p:

We start by working out the components of each of the three velocity vectors. The components of  \vec v_1  and  \vec v_2  do not give us any trouble.

	 \amp v_{1x} = 25.0\text{ m/s},\ \ v_{1y} = 0
	 \amp v_{2x} = 21.65\text{ m/s},\ \ v_{2y} = 12.5\text{ m/s}

sidebyside.p:
However, we need to be careful when we work on  \vec v_3  since the vector is pointed in the second quadrant of the  xy  plane. 
When we peoject the arrow of the vector  \vec v_3  on the  x  axis, we strike the negative  x  axis, which means that  v_{3x} \lt 0 , i.e., negative.

	 \amp v_{3x} = -v_3\, \cos(|\theta|) = -34.64\text{ m/s}
	 \amp v_{3y} = +v_3\, \sin(|\theta|) = +20.0\text{ m/s}

solution.p:
Let us denote the sum by symbol \vec V. The x- and y-components of the sum will be equal to the sum of the x- and y-components of the other vectors.
\amp V_x = (3\ \textrm{m/s}) + (9\ \textrm{m/s}) = 12\ \textrm{m/s}
\amp V_y = (2\ \textrm{m/s}) + (11\ \textrm{m/s}) + (-8\ \textrm{m/s}) = 5\ \textrm{m/s}.

 			Let \vec F_1 be the vector at 60^{\circ} from the x axis and \vec F_2 be the other vector.The components of \vec F_1 and \vec F_2 are

	 			\amp 
	 				F_{1x} = (100\ \textrm{N}) \cos(60^{\circ}) = 50\ \textrm{N}

	 			\amp
	 				F_{1y} = (100\ \textrm{N}) \sin(60^{\circ}) = 86.6\ \textrm{N}

	 			\amp 
	 				F_{2x} = -100\ \textrm{N}

	 			\amp 
	 				F_{2y} = 0
